  "prompt": "How were nuclear reactor cores designed before the use of advanced computer modelling?",
  "response": "Before the advent of advanced computer modeling, the design of nuclear reactor cores relied heavily on empirical data, theoretical calculations, and a combination of experience and experimental validation. Here are some key methods and approaches used in the design of nuclear reactor cores prior to modern computational tools:\n\n1. **Analytical Calculations**: Early reactor designers used fundamental theories in nuclear physics and engineering to perform analytical calculations. They derived equations governing reactor physics, such as neutron diffusion and neutron multiplication factors, and used these equations to understand reactor behavior.\n\n2. **Empirical Data**: Much of the design was informed by empirical data gathered from earlier reactor designs and experiments. Engineers used results from small-scale tests and experiments to inform their designs for larger reactors, adjusting parameters based on observed performance.\n\n3. **Mock-ups and Prototyping**: Physical models and prototypes of reactor cores were constructed to experimentally observe their behavior. This approach allowed engineers to test theories and assumptions in a controlled environment before full-scale deployment.\n\n4. **Hand Calculations**: Safety factors, reactivity coefficients, and thermal hydraulic calculations were performed using hand calculations and slide rules. This approach was time-consuming but allowed for a detailed understanding of reactor kinetics and dynamics.\n\n5. **Historical Precedents**: Early nuclear engineers often relied on existing reactor designs. They studied the experiences and designs of pioneering reactors (like the Chicago Pile-1 and the first commercial reactors) and applied lessons learned to new designs.\n\n6. **Design Guides and Standards**: Various design guides, regulatory frameworks, and standards were established over time, which specified certain criteria and best practices to ensure safety and efficiency in reactor design.\n\n7. **Collaboration and Peer Review**: Designers often relied on collaboration with other experienced engineers, physicists, and institutions. Peer review in the academic and professional community provided a feedback loop that helped validate designs.\n\n8. **Intuition and Experience**: A considerable aspect of reactor design before advanced modeling was guided by the intuition and experience of skilled engineers. Their hands-on experience and understanding of the phenomena at play were invaluable in the design process.\n\nWhile early designs could be limited in precision and optimization compared to modern approaches, they set the foundation for the more complex and efficient systems used today, which are heavily supported by advanced computer simulations and modeling techniques.",
